<article>
    <h1>Go with the grain</h1>
    <h2>Here are five fried rice dishes worth spend&#xAD;ing your carb quota on</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201115/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-15"><time>2020-11-15</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | FOOD &amp; DRINK</span>
        - <span role="byline">Eu&#xAD;nice Quek&#xD;&#xA;Food Cor&#xAD;re&#xAD;spon&#xAD;dent eu&#xAD;niceq@sph.com.sg&#xD;&#xA;Fol&#xAD;low The Straits Times Food on Face&#xAD;book and In&#xAD;sta&#xAD;gram @strait&#xAD;stimes&#xAD;food</span>
    </section>

    <p>There has been much ado about fried rice since London-based Malaysian co­me­dian Nigel Ng – bet­ter known as Un­cle Roger – scathingly re­viewed BBC Food pre­sen­ter Her­sha Pa­tel’s method of cook­ing egg fried rice on his YouTube chan­nel.</p>
    <p>Since that video went vi­ral in July, he has done more sear­ing fried rice com­men­taries. One in­cluded tak­ing apart celebrity chef Jamie Oliver’s ver­sion that uses chilli jam. He was, how­ever, more ap­prov­ing of chef Gor­don Ram­say’s fairly au­then­tic ren­di­tion of spicy fried rice cooked in West Su­ma­tra, In­done­sia.</p>
    <p>In Sin­ga­pore, it is fried rice paradise once more as peo­ple crave com­fort foods, es­pe­cially carbs, in un­cer­tain times. The hum­ble rice dish, some­times jazzed up with new in­gre­di­ents, has be­come a sta­ple or­der again at many zichar stalls, as well as restau­rants.</p>
    <p>It is also the hero dish that has launched brands, such as the ha­lal-cer­ti­fied chain of fried rice kiosks Wok Hey, which has over 10 out­lets, and King Of Fried Rice, with out­lets at Golden Mile Tower and Sengkang’s Ko­pi­tiam Square.</p>
    <p>The Sun­day Times picks five fried rice dishes that Un­cle Roger would ap­prove of.</p>

